Here's a simple example of how MVP could be implemented in a login functionality:

Model:
```
public class User {
    private String username;
    private String password;

    public User(String username, String password) {
        this.username = username;
        this.password = password;
    }

    public boolean isValid() {
        return this.username.equals("admin") && this.password.equals("password123");
    }
}
```

View:
```
public interface LoginView {
    String getUsername();
    String getPassword();
    void showInvalidCredentialsError();
    void showSuccessMessage();
}
```

Presenter:
```
public class LoginPresenter {
    private LoginView view;

    public LoginPresenter(LoginView view) {
        this.view = view;
    }

    public void onLoginButtonClicked() {
        String username = view.getUsername();
        String password = view.getPassword();
        User user = new User(username, password);

        if (user.isValid()) {
            view.showSuccessMessage();
        } else {
            view.showInvalidCredentialsError();
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, the Model is represented by the User class, which stores the username and password and checks whether the credentials are valid. The View is represented by the LoginView interface, which defines the methods to get the username and password from the user and to show error messages. The Presenter is represented by the LoginPresenter class, which acts as a mediator between the Model and the View. It handles the login functionality and updates the View based on the result. 

The View is implemented separately, and the Presenter is passed to the View as a parameter. The Presenter is responsible for handling the user actions (in this case, when the login button is clicked) and updating the View based on the result.

Here's an example of implementing MVP in JavaScript for a simple calculator application:

Model:
```
class CalculatorModel {
    constructor() {
        this.result = 0;
    }

    add(num1, num2) {
        this.result = num1 + num2;
    }

    subtract(num1, num2) {
        this.result = num1 - num2;
    }

    multiply(num1, num2) {
        this.result = num1 * num2;
    }

    divide(num1, num2) {
        if (num2 === 0) {
            throw new Error("Cannot divide by zero");
        }
        this.result = num1 / num2;
    }
}
```

View:
```
class CalculatorView {
    constructor() {
        this.firstNumberInput = document.getElementById("firstNumberInput");
        this.secondNumberInput = document.getElementById("secondNumberInput");
        this.addButton = document.getElementById("addButton");
        this.subtractButton = document.getElementById("subtractButton");
        this.multiplyButton = document.getElementById("multiplyButton");
        this.divideButton = document.getElementById("divideButton");
        this.resultOutput = document.getElementById("resultOutput");

        this.addButton.addEventListener("click", this.onAddClicked.bind(this));
        this.subtractButton.addEventListener("click", this.onSubtractClicked.bind(this));
        this.multiplyButton.addEventListener("click", this.onMultiplyClicked.bind(this));
        this.divideButton.addEventListener("click", this.onDivideClicked.bind(this));
    }

    onAddClicked() {
        this.onCalculationClicked("+");
    }

    onSubtractClicked() {
        this.onCalculationClicked("-");
    }

    onMultiplyClicked() {
        this.onCalculationClicked("*");
    }

    onDivideClicked() {
        this.onCalculationClicked("/");
    }

    onCalculationClicked(operator) {
        const num1 = parseFloat(this.firstNumberInput.value);
        const num2 = parseFloat(this.secondNumberInput.value);
        this.displayResult(operator, num1, num2);
    }

    displayResult(operator, num1, num2) {
        this.resultOutput.innerText = `${num1} ${operator} ${num2} = `;
    }

    updateResult(result) {
        this.resultOutput.innerText += result;
    }

    showError(error) {
        alert(error.message);
    }
}
```

Presenter:
```
class CalculatorPresenter {
    constructor(model, view) {
        this.model = model;
        this.view = view;
    }

    onAddClicked(num1, num2) {
        this.performCalculation(this.model.add.bind(this.model), num1, num2);
    }

    onSubtractClicked(num1, num2) {
        this.performCalculation(this.model.subtract.bind(this.model), num1, num2);
    }

    onMultiplyClicked(num1, num2) {
        this.performCalculation(this.model.multiply.bind(this.model), num1, num2);
    }

    onDivideClicked(num1, num2) {
        this.performCalculation(this.model.divide.bind(this.model), num1, num2);
    }

    performCalculation(op, num1, num2) {
        try {
            op(num1, num2);
            this.view.updateResult(this.model.result);
        } catch (error) {
            this.view.showError(error);
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, the Model is represented by the CalculatorModel class, which performs the calculations and stores the result in a property. The View is represented by the CalculatorView class, which handles the user interface and user inputs. The Presenter is represented by the CalculatorPresenter class, which mediates between the Model and the View.

The View listens to the user actions and sends them to the Presenter, which then interacts with the Model to perform the calculation. The result is then sent back to the View for display. If there is an error, the Presenter sends the error message to the View for display.

