Here is an example of a simple MVC (Model-View-Controller) pattern using JavaScript:

Model:

```
let data = [];

function addData(item) {
  data.push(item);
}

function getData() {
  return data;
}
```

View:

```
const view = (function() {
  const list = document.querySelector('#list');

  function render(items) {
    let html = '';
    items.forEach(item => {
      html += `<li>${item}</li>`;
    });
    list.innerHTML = html;
  }

  return {
    render
  };
})();
```

Controller:

```
const controller = (function(model, view) {
  const form = document.querySelector('#form');
  const input = document.querySelector('#item');

  function init() {
    form.addEventListener('submit', addItem);
    view.render(model.getData());
  }

  function addItem(e) {
    e.preventDefault();
    const item = input.value;
    model.addData(item);
    view.render(model.getData());
    input.value = '';
  }

  return {
    init
  };
})(model, view);

controller.init();
```

This example shows a simple to-do list application. The model represents the data of the application, which is an array of items. The view is responsible for rendering the data to the screen, and the controller handles user actions and updates the model and view accordingly. 

The init function in the controller sets up event listeners and calls the view to render the initial data. The addItem function is called when the user submits a new item through the form. The function adds the new item to the model, updates the view, and clears the input field.

