Here's an updated example of the MVC pattern in JavaScript to illustrate this:

Model:

```
class Model {
  constructor() {
    this.data = [];
  }

  addData(item) {
    this.data.push(item);
  }

  getData() {
    return this.data;
  }
}
```

View:

```
class View {
  constructor() {
    this.list = document.querySelector('#list');
    this.form = document.querySelector('#form');
    this.input = document.querySelector('#item');
  }

  render(items) {
    let html = '';
    items.forEach(item => {
      html += `<li>${item}</li>`;
    });
    this.list.innerHTML = html;
  }

  addItemHandler(callback) {
    this.form.addEventListener('submit', e => {
      e.preventDefault();
      const item = this.input.value;
      callback(item);
      this.input.value = '';
    });
  }
}
```

Controller:

```
class Controller {
  constructor(model, view) {
    this.model = model;
    this.view = view;
    this.view.addItemHandler(this.addItem.bind(this));
    this.updateView();
  }

  addItem(item) {
    this.model.addData(item);
    this.updateView();
  }

  updateView() {
    const data = this.model.getData();
    this.view.render(data);
  }
}

const app = new Controller(new Model(), new View());
```

In this example, the View has an addItemHandler method that takes a callback function as an argument. The method listens for the submit event of the form and calls the callback function with the input value. The callback function is provided by the Controller and interacts with the Model.

The Controller sets up the event listener for the View's form submission and also defines the logic for adding an item to the Model. It binds its methods to its instance to ensure that "this" always refers to the Controller's instance.

The Controller's updateView method retrieves the data from the Model and renders it on the View by calling the View's render method. 

Overall, the View is responsible for rendering the data and sending user input to the Controller. The Controller acts as the intermediary between the View and the Model, processing user input and updating the Model, and updating the View with the new data. The Model is responsible for managing the application data.

